[src:commander-cli/commander-js] When `.command()` is invoked with a description argument, this tells Commander that you're going to use stand-alone executables for subcommands.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] Commander will search the files in the directory of the entry script for a file with the name combination `command-subcommand` (like `pm-install` or `pm-search` in the example below).
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] The search includes trying common file extensions, like `.js`.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] You may specify a custom name (and path) with the `executableFile` configuration option.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] You may specify a custom search directory for subcommands with `.executableDir()`.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] You handle the options for an executable (sub)command in the executable, and don't declare them at the top-level.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] If the program is designed to be installed globally, make sure the executables have proper modes, like `755`.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] You can add callback hooks to a command for life cycle events.
