[src:commander-cli/commander-js] The help by default lists options under the the heading `Options:` and commands under `Commands:`.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] You can create your own groups with different headings.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] The built-in help is formatted using the `Help` class.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] You can configure the help by modifying data properties and methods using `.configureHelp()`, or by subclassing `Help` using `.createHelp()` .
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] Simple properties include `sortSubcommands`, `sortOptions`, and `showGlobalOptions`.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] You can add color using the style methods like `.styleTitle()`.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] For more detail and examples of changing the displayed text, color, and layout, see: Help in Depth.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] You can execute custom actions by listening to `command` and `option` events.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] Call with no parameters to parse `process.argv`.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] Detects Electron and special node options like `node --eval`.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] Use `.parseAsync()` instead of `.parse()` if any of your action handlers are async.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] If the default parsing does not suit your needs, there are some behaviours to support other usage patterns.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] By default, program options are recognised before and after subcommands.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] To only look for program options before subcommands, use `.enablePositionalOptions()`.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] This lets you use an option for a different purpose in subcommands.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] By default, options are recognised before and after command-arguments.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] To only process options that come before the command-arguments, use `.passThroughOptions()`.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] This lets you pass the arguments and following options through to another program without needing to use `--` to end the option processing.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] To use pass through options in a subcommand, the program needs to enable positional options.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] By default, the option processing shows an error for an unknown option.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] To have an unknown option treated as an ordinary command-argument and continue looking for options, use `.allowUnknownOption()`.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] This lets you mix known and unknown options.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] By default, the argument processing displays an error for more command-arguments than expected.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] To suppress the error for excess arguments, use `.allowExcessArguments()`.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] Before Commander 7, the option values were stored as properties on the command.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] This was convenient to code, but the downside was possible clashes with existing properties of `Command`.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] You can revert to the old behaviour to run unmodified legacy code by using `.storeOptionsAsProperties()`.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] This factory function creates a new command.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] `createCommand()` is also a method of the `Command` object, and creates a new command rather than a subcommand.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] This gets used internally when creating subcommands using `.command()`, and you may override it to customise the new subcommand.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] An executable subcommand is launched as a separate child process.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] If you are using the node inspector for debugging executable subcommands using `node --inspect` et al., the inspector port is incremented by 1 for the spawned subcommand.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] If you are using VSCode to debug executable subcommands you need to set the `"autoAttachChildProcesses": true` flag in your `launch.json` configuration.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] By default, when you call your program using `run-script`, `npm` will parse any options on the command-line and they will not reach your program.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] Use `--` to stop the npm option parsing and pass through all the arguments.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] This routine is available to invoke the Commander error handling for your own error conditions.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] As well as the error message, you can optionally specify the `exitCode` (used with `process.exit()`) and `code` (used with `CommanderError`).
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] By default, Commander calls `process.exit()` when it detects errors, or after displaying the help or version.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] You can override this behaviour and optionally supply a callback.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] The default override throws a `CommanderError`.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] Commander expects the callback to terminate the normal program flow, and will call `process.exit()` if the callback returns.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] The normal display of error messages or version or help is not affected by the override, which is called after the display.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] By default, Commander is configured for a command-line application and writes to stdout and stderr.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] You can modify this behaviour for custom applications.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] In addition, you can modify the display of error messages.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] The current version of Commander is fully supported on Long Term Support versions of Node.js, and requires at least v22.12.0.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] Older major versions of Commander receive security updates for 12 months.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] The main forum for free and community support is the project Issues on GitHub.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] The maintainers of Commander and thousands of other packages are working with Tidelift to deliver commercial support and maintenance for the open source dependencies you use to build your applications.
[src:commander-cli/commander-js] Save time, reduce risk, and improve code health, while paying the maintainers of the exact dependencies you use.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] The getopt function was written to be a standard mechanism that all programs could use to parse command-line options so that there would be a common interface on which everyone could depend.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] As such, the original authors picked out of the variations support for single character options, multiple options specified together, and options with arguments (`-a arg` or `-aarg`), all controllable by an option string.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] getopt dates back to at least 1980 and was first published by AT&T at the 1985 UNIFORUM conference in Dallas, Texas, with the intent for it to be available in the public domain.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] Versions of it were subsequently picked up by other flavors of Unix (4.3BSD, Linux, etc.).
[src:commander-cli/getopt] It is specified in the POSIX.2 standard as part of the unistd.h header file.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] Derivatives of getopt have been created for many programming languages to parse command-line options.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] A POSIX-standard companion function to `getopt` is `getsubopt`.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] It parses a string of comma-separated sub-options.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] getopt is a system dependent function, and its behavior depends on the implementation in the C library.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] Some custom implementations like gnulib are available, however.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] The conventional (POSIX and BSD) handling is that the options end when the first non-option argument is encountered, and that getopt would return -1 to signal that.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] In the glibc extension, however, options are allowed *anywhere* for ease of use; getopt implicitly permutes the argument vector so it still leaves the non-options in the end.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] Since POSIX already has the convention of returning -1 on `--` and skipping it, one can always portably use it as an end-of-options signifier.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] A GNU extension, **getopt_long**, allows parsing of more readable, multicharacter options, which are introduced by two dashes instead of one.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] The choice of two dashes allows multicharacter options (`--inum`) to be differentiated from single character options specified together (`-abc`).
[src:commander-cli/getopt] The GNU extension also allows an alternative format for options with arguments: `--name=arg`.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] This interface proved popular, and has been taken up (sans the permutation) by many BSD distributions including FreeBSD as well as Solaris.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] An alternative way to support long options is seen in Solaris and Korn Shell (extending *optstring*), but it was not as popular.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] Another common advanced extension of getopt is resetting the state of argument parsing; this is useful as a replacement of the options-anyware GNU extension, or as a way to "layer" a set of command-line interface with different options at different levels.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] This is achieved in BSD systems using an optreset variable, and on GNU systems by setting optind to 0.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] The command-line syntaxes for getopt-based programs is the POSIX-recommended Utility Argument Syntax.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] Extensions on the syntax include the GNU convention and Sun's CLIP specification.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] Here the `argc` and `argv` are defined exactly like they are in the C `main` function prototype; i.e., `argc` indicates the length of the `argv` array of C-strings.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] The `optstring` contains a specification of what options to look for (normal alphanumerals except `W`), and what options to accept arguments (colons).
[src:commander-cli/getopt] For example, `"vf::o:"` refers to three options: an argumentless `v`, an optional-argument `f`, and a mandatory-argument `o`.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] GNU here implements a `W` extension for long option synonyms.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] `getopt` itself returns an `int` that is either an option `char` or `-1` for end-of-options.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] The idiom is to use a `while`-loop to go through options, and to use a `switch`-`case` statement to pick and act on options.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] See the example section of this article.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] The GNU extension `getopt_long` interface is similar, although it belongs to a different header file and takes an extra option for defining the "short" names of long options and some extra controls.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] If a short name is not defined, `getopt` will put an index referring to the option structure in the `longindex` pointer instead.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] Shell script programmers commonly want to provide a consistent way of providing options.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] To achieve this goal, they turn to getopts and seek to port it to their own language.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] The first attempt at porting was the program *getopt*, implemented by Unix System Laboratories (USL).
[src:commander-cli/getopt] This version was unable to deal with quoting and shell metacharacters, as it shows no attempts at quoting.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] In 1986, USL decided that being unsafe around metacharacters and whitespace was no longer acceptable, and they created the builtin getopts command for Unix SVR3 Bourne Shell instead.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] The advantage of building the command into the shell is that it now has access to the shell's variables, so values could be written safely without quoting.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] It uses the shell's own variables to track the position of current and argument positions, OPTIND and OPTARG, and returns the option name in a shell variable.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] In 1995, `getopts` was included in the Single UNIX Specification version 1 / X/Open Portability Guidelines Issue 4.
[src:commander-cli/getopt] Now a part of the POSIX Shell standard, getopts have spread far and wide in many other shells trying to be POSIX-compliant.
